ton, Lancashire, England":"Chorlton, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Townley","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Lancashire): habitational name from Towneley near Burnley in Lancashire, which is named with Middle English <i>toun(e)</i>, <i>ton(e)</i> ‘town, village, settlement’ (Old English <i>tūn</i>) + <i>leie</i> ‘glade, clearing’. The surname has also been established in Ireland since the 16th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Townsley","meanings":["English (northern): variant of   Townley  . In Ireland this name was confused with   Tinsley  ."]},{"name":"Thomley","meanings":["English (Lancashire): variant of   Townley  . This form of the surname is rare in Britain and Ireland."]}]},{"name":"Matilda","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Mathilda","meanings":["Old German: Mighty battle maid"]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Matilda Townley was born in 1241, in Chorlton, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom, her father, John Townley, was 27 and her mother, Elizabeth de Rixton, was 24. She married Sir Richard Barlow about 1265, in Chorlton, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"1241–":"12